            "abstractNote": "Pollination biology, ﬂoral characteristics, nectar secretion and breeding system of a Cuban endemic plant that grows mainly on ultramaﬁc soils, the legume Caesalpinia bahamensis Lam. subsp. orientensis Borhidi, were studied in the ultramaﬁc vegetation area of the National Botanical Garden in Havana, Cuba. Caesalpinia bahamensis showed ﬂoral characteristics typical of chiropterophily. The corolla, with its small inconspicuous greenish-whitish lobes, is reduced in comparison to other species of the genus. Buds opened late in the evening and each ﬂower bloomed only for a single night. Nectar secretion was nocturnal. Mean sugar concentration of the nectar was 14% (w/w) and mean total nectar production was 205 ␮l per ﬂower. The species is xenogamous, as selfed ﬂowers were abscised. The natural fruiting success was low (less than 10%). The main visitor and pollinator was the glossophagine bat Monophyllus redmani Leach 1821.",
